For training scenarios - prepacking will be disabled by default and if user explicitly enables it then an error will be thrown.

Enable both optimized inference as well as on device training in a single build. For on device training use flag --enable_training_apis.

### Description
In this file, `onnxruntime/blob/main/tools/python/util/run.py`, the default value for the check argument is `True`. The value of the check argument goes to the python built-in function `subprocess.run`. This function, in the python 3.8 version, will raise a `CalledProcesserror` if the check argument is `True`. It would be problematic, for example, in the file `/onnxruntime/blob/main/tools/ci_build/build.py` at line 739, function `run_subprocess` uses this function. But, no value for the check argument is passed, even in `args`. Therefore, by default, It would lead to a `CalledProcesserror`. 



### Motivation and Context
I just turn the default value of the check argument to `False`.

title: Creating an inference session takes longer when there are many sessions already created

labels.name: core runtime
labels.description: issues related to core runtime

body:
### Describe the issue

I'm trying to create a large number (~10 thousand) of ONNX sessions in a single process. Since the model is very small, when I create a single session, it is usually very fast to load (sub millisecond). However, when I load a large number of models, some of the sessions being created take an enormous amount of time (seconds). Initially I thought that there might be some quadratic behaviour, but when I plot the times it doesn't seem quadratic, rather there are some really large outliers:

(x axis = loading of n-th model copy, y axis = time in seconds)
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/4539057/212021774-efa5db87-8b0e-4e08-af6d-382c7da13da1.png)

When I simply create the sessions and immediately free them, this doesn't happen and everything is fast. So it seems like it might be caused by some perf. hit when ONNX accesses some shared data structues when there are already a lot of sessions loaded in memory, for example false sharing or other multithreading issue. The chart above is for 8 threads (the default that `onnxruntime` uses on my system). When I force a single thread, everything is mostly fast as expected:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/4539057/212023685-8d0aa2c5-f807-4912-a5e5-db3182754d20.png)

I experimented with `SessionOptions` a bit and the slowdown happens when I set `opts.intra_op_num_threads` to a value larger than one (the higher the value, the slower it is).

### To reproduce

```python
import sys
import time

import onnxruntime as ort
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

opts = ort.SessionOptions()
# This causes it to be slow
opts.intra_op_num_threads = 8

count = 1000
models = []

times = []
for _ in range(count):
    start = time.time()
    # executing just `ort.InferenceSession(...)` without storing the returned object also removes the bottleneck
    models.append(ort.InferenceSession("_model_1.onnx", sess_options=opts))
    duration = time.time() - start
    times.append(duration)

sns.lineplot(x=list(range(len(times))), y=times)
plt.show()

print("load", duration, (duration / count))
sys.stdout.flush()
```

title: TensorRT engine cache fails due to ever increasing integer in engine filename

labels.name: ep:CUDA

labels.name: ep:TensorRT
labels.description: issues related to TensorRT execution provider

labels.name: platform:windows
labels.description: issues related to the Windows platform

body:
### Describe the issue

TensorRT EP generates engine cache files with ever increasing integers in filenames for new Sessions. Therefore, it never finds an existing cache file in the same process. It is required to stop/kill the process and restart for an engine cache to be found.

### To reproduce

* Create C++ app that uses given setup and config of this issue.
* App must create Ort::Env once on startup. Then with a ui element or keypress create/run/destroy an Ort::Session with the same model_file. The whole time, the app continues running with its single Env.
* App should use the TensorRT EP and configure it with...
```c++
OrtTensorRTProviderOptions options{};
options.device_id = 0; // code the device id needed
options.trt_max_workspace_size = 2ull * 1024 * 1024 * 1024; // same as default yet prevents warnings in console
options.trt_max_partition_iterations = 1000;                // same as default yet prevents warnings in console
options.trt_min_subgraph_size = 1;                          // same as default yet prevents warnings in console
options.trt_engine_cache_enable = 1;
options.trt_engine_cache_path = "C:\\blahblah\\mycustomdirectory";
session_options.AppendExecutionProvider_TensorRT(options);
session = Ort::Session(onnx_env, model_file.c_str(), session_options);
```

1. Run app. This creates an `Env`
2. Load model1 onnx file. This creates a `Session`. Many seconds later (mine takes 105 seconds) the session will start and you will see an engine file appear in the cache directory.
3. Cause the Session to gracefully stop/end. **Your app and Env are still running**
4. Again, load model1 onnx file. This creates a `Session`. Many seconds later (mine takes 105 seconds) the session will start and you will see a 2nd engine file appear in the cache directory.
5. Cause the Session to gracefully stop/end. **Your app and Env are still running**
6. Again, load model1 onnx file. This creates a `Session`. Many seconds later (mine takes 105 seconds) the session will start and you will see a 3rd engine file appear in the cache directory.
7. Stop/kill your app and its process.
8. Run app. This creates an `Env`
9. Load model1 onnx file. This creates a `Session`. In 1 or 2 seconds, the TensorRT EP will load a cached engine file and your session will start.
10. Cause the Session to gracefully stop/end. **Your app and Env are still running**
11. Again, load model1 onnx file. This creates a `Session`. In 1 or 2 seconds, the TensorRT EP will load a cached engine file and your session will start.
12. Cause the Session to gracefully stop/end. **Your app and Env are still running**
13. Again, load model1 onnx file. This creates a `Session`. In 1 or 2 seconds, the TensorRT EP will load a cached engine file and your session will start.
14. Cause the Session to gracefully stop/end. **Your app and Env are still running**
15. Again, load model1 onnx file. This creates a `Session`. Many seconds later (mine takes 105 seconds) the session will start and you will see a 4th engine file appear in the cache directory.

I suspect there is some global counter that is part of the generation of cache filenames. Every time a Session is started, this global counter is incremented. Therefore when the Session ends and a new Session starts (in the same app), its global counter has incremented higher than the already existing cache file. This means that cache files are never found unless the app is killed and therefore the global counter is reset.

When I isolated this in my app, I never got cache usage yet generated 4 engine cache files.
This is EXACTLY the same app config, model file, and even the same process.
Notice the `_1_` that increments +2 on each start of each Session.
```
TensorrtExecutionProvider_TRTKernel_graph_tf2onnx_18389142000517052976_1_0.engine
TensorrtExecutionProvider_TRTKernel_graph_tf2onnx_18389142000517052976_3_0.engine
TensorrtExecutionProvider_TRTKernel_graph_tf2onnx_18389142000517052976_5_0.engine
TensorrtExecutionProvider_TRTKernel_graph_tf2onnx_18389142000517052976_7_0.engine
```

I suspect the first session looks for `_1_`, doesn't find it, and then creates `_1_`
I suspect the second session looks for `_3_`, doesn't find it, and then creates `_3_`
I suspect the third session looks for `_5_`, doesn't find it, and then creates `_5_`
...and it repeats forever.

But on app/process kill and restart...
First session looks for `_1_`, finds and loads the cached engine.
Second session looks for `_3_`, finds and loads the cached engine.
Third session looks for `_5_`, finds and loads the cached engine.
Fourth session looks for `_7_`, doesn't find it, and then creates `_7_`

Logs of it loading cached engine files proving it is incrementing a counter and loading the cache file using that counter
```
onnxruntime:0 [tensorrt_execution_provider.cc:1333 onnxruntime::TensorrtExecutionProvider::Compile] [TensorRT EP] DeSerialized C:\Users\dale\AppData\Local\Temp\dp.oak\onnx.cache\vNgj4DQ6DoYtrYc5RUZLGz45KmY\TensorrtExecutionProvider_TRTKernel_graph_tf2onnx_18389142000517052976_1_0.engine
onnxruntime:0 [tensorrt_execution_provider.cc:1333 onnxruntime::TensorrtExecutionProvider::Compile] [TensorRT EP] DeSerialized C:\Users\dale\AppData\Local\Temp\dp.oak\onnx.cache\vNgj4DQ6DoYtrYc5RUZLGz45KmY\TensorrtExecutionProvider_TRTKernel_graph_tf2onnx_18389142000517052976_3_0.engine

```

Also strange is the dramatic difference in file sizes of the cached engine files. Again this is EXACTLY the same app config, model file, and they were saved in the same process. Smallest to largest is 56972 bytes, or 0.3% of its file size.

Unless I have overlooked something, it seems that the current C-api does not support propagating a failure in the `KernelCompute` call of a custom operator. While some functions in the public c-api return status pointers this is not true for the compute function (and kernel creation). ~~Unless this functionality already exists somewhere, I am afraid that it would not be possible to extend the existing API in a backwards compatible way. Implementing such error propagation would require a "version 2" of the custom operator API, as far as I can tell. Is this in the realm of possibilities?~~ I think #16479 presents a pretty clean way to implement this feature.

### Describe scenario use case

title: Unit test modification for TensorRT EP
body:
Two modifications:

- After [TRT 8.5](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/13867) being merged, we can manually set timeout and make TRT EP only run small portion of unit tests (`onnxruntime_SKIP_AND_PERFORM_FILTERED_TENSORRT_TESTS=ON`) due to additional TRT kernel overhead introduced by TRT 8.5 which increases test time a lot. This PR modifies the checking condition and make TensorRT CIs (can enable builder placeholder) still run most of the unit tests. 
- Exclude TRT EP from [Resize Opset 18](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/13890) unit tests since TensorRT 8.5 supports operators up to Opset 17.
